In article <01050810.th0mox@mbeckman.mbeckman.com>, mbeckman@mbeckman.mbeckman.com (Mel Beckman) writes:
|> All this is irrelevant anyway. The Copyright Office only requires registration
|> of "identifying materials" -- NOT the entire body of source code for a program.
|> Specifically, only the first and last 25 pages of "visually perceivable"
|> material is necessary. This could be an object code dump (if you don't distribute
|> source code) or simply some innocuous parts of your program (if you do)
|> -- who is to say what the "first" and "last" parts of any program are? They
|> need not be what is logically first and last, only physically in your organization.

Actually, you are allowed to block out up to 50% of the code in the
first/last 25 pages.  There are other combinations permissible,
apparently.  For all the gory details, pick up the most recent issue of
Dr. Dobbs' Journal (March or April '93) for the article, "How to
Copyright Software."
